Switzerland Gov *5............... 113%\nUh Kin* of G B A Ire 6%5.. 185%\nJTTOWITT\nsued ay k\n1\nRolland L. Nutt, an attorney, with\noffice* in the McLachlan Building,\ntoday wan named defendant in a\nSuit by hia wife, Henrietta Roger*\nNutt, of J2OS Fourteenth St. N. K\u201e\nfor a limited divorce and separate\nmaintenance.\nMr*. Nutt, through her attorneys,\nHarry A. and C. P. Grant, tell* th*\ncourt that *he and her husband\ni were married in 1917 and were happy\nuntil a year ago. They have two\nchildren.\nIn September of last year, she\nsays, she discovered her husband\ni hugging another wgmsn in an auto\nmobile. She remonstrated with him,\nshe says, and he grew angry.\nFinally, on September Bof thl*\ni year, she says that he deserted her\nand only comas home while she is\na wa\nssuUMm*\nINSIST\u2014On the delivery of\nyour Times nr Herald every\nK you d y\u00ae Br\nHerald by 7a. The\nTime\u00ae by sp.m\u201e er The\nSunday Herald by 8 a. m.,\ncall Main 5260. Delivery is\ni fuaranteed and your copy\nwill be sent you immediately\ni from the Time* Corpany\nOffice by apodal moMen<er.\nCODNTY FIGHTS\nALEXANDHIA\nARLINGTON COUNTY, Sept. 24.\n\u2014Every effort will be made to\nblock the movement for the an\nnexation ot any part of Arlington\nCountry by the city of Alexandria,\naccording to Commonwealth's At\ntorney William C. Cloth.\n\u201cThe moment actual proceedings\nlooking to the annexation of one\nsquare inch of the territory of\nArlington County by Alexandria is\nstarted I will fight the case to\nthe utmost,\u2019\u2019 declared Gloth.\n\"Arlington County is far super\nior in improvements today to Alex\nandria and Alexandria is not en\ntitled to one inch of the territory\nof Arlington County.\nAldington County\u2019s unit of the\nGreater Washington Motor Club\nWas organized At a meeting, last\nnight at the Little Tea -Hou\u00bb\u00bb\nRobert E. Plymale was elected\npresident. Charles R. Taylor first\nvice president; Charles W. Smith,\nsecond vice president; W. M. Stone,\ntreasurer;' and Walter U. Varney\nsecretary.\nGeorge E. Garrett, and William\nP. Ames, were elected to the board\nof directors of the Greatest Wash\nington Motor Club as the represen\ntatives from the local organization.\nThe board of governors of the\nlocal club are besides the officers.\nWilliam P. Ames. M. E. Church.\nWilliam Coates. H. K. Green. W.\nK. Handy. E. D. Collins. John R.\nHarding. A. B. Honta. Ashton C.\n.Tones, Fletcher Kemp, C. W. Smith.\nFred Windridge. Milford Witts, and\nA. M. Dawson.\nJesse C. Suter, president of the\nGreatest Washington Motor Club\nand Raymond Beck, general man\nager. spoke.\nThe enrollment of the three\ncolored schools In Arlington County\nis 422. The enrollment by schools\nis Kemper. 138. Jefferson, 174, and\nJohn M. Langston, school. 110.\nThe enrollment of the 22 schools\nin the county has far exceeded\nthe 5,000 mark. Fletcher Kemp,\ncountry school superintendant,\nsaid today.\nThere will be a mass meeting\nof the colored voters of. Arlington\nCounty Monday night at Harrison's\nPark. Hall's Hill, at 8 o\u2019clock. All\ncandidates for county officers will\nspeak.\nW. B. HIBBS CO. I\nMEMBERS 1\nNEW YORK STOCK EXCHANGE I\nBOSTON STOCK EXCHANGE\nPHILADELPHIA STOCK EXCHANGE\nWASHINGTON STOCK EXCHANGE\nNEW YORK COTTON EXCHANGE\nCHICAGO BOARD OF TRADE\nH NEW YORK CURB MARKET\nHIBBS BUILDING I\n72S 15th St. WaMngton, D. C.\n7\nHE PERSONAL SIDE of j\nW oodrow Wilson at last revealed f\nin the most remarkable biography f\npublished in our generation!\nA work of the utmost importance to\neveryone who wants to know the inside\nhistory of America's part in the World\nWar\u2014and the intimate life of the man\nwhose words dominated the world.\nLife andletters of\nB V RAY STANNARD BAKER\nDaily Installments Begin\nTomorrow\nm\nBig Sunda/\ntteralo\nD. C. Heads to Proceed\nWith New Garnet School\nReversing a previou* decision, the\nDistrict Commissioner* have voted\nto go ahead with construction of the\nGarnet-Patterson J Junior High\nSchool and have Awarded th* (Rm\ntract to the Chartes H. Tompkins\nCompany, of thi* city.\nA lack of funds forced th* Com\nmissioners to omit -the gymnasium\nand to forego razing part of the old\nbuilding. The cdntract called for a\nprice of 1372.240 and contained a\nproviso that if the District can ob\ntain additional appropriations the\nomitted work will be done for 3158.-\n720 more.\nRates of annual tuition tor pupil*\nnot entitled to free entry were fixed\nby the Commissioners, as follows:\nNormal schools, $183.67: high\nschools, $131.13: junior high schools,\n.$116.44; elementary schools, $67.23:\nspecial achodlg, $137.17: vocational\nschools; $158.17; vacation schools.\n$3.94; night Schools, $9.74.\n5 to Head West for\nWar Mothers\u2019 Meet\nMr*. Martha C. O\u2019Neill. Mrs. E. C.\nWagner. Mrs. Anna Shanahan. Mrs.\nLucy Cash and Mrs. Anna Walter*\nwill leave today tor Milwaukee to at\ntend the annual convention of the\nAmerican War Mothers, as delegates\nfrom the Washington Chapter.\nAt a meeting last night of the\nchapter in the Hotel Hamilton they\nwere instructed to urge passage of a\nresolution which would place dis\nabled emergency officers on the\nsame footing as to pay as disabled\nofficers of the regular army.\nM. Street Bridge Plan\nApproved by Arts Body\nThe Commission of Fine Arts in\nformed the District Commissioners\nyesterday that they had approved\nplans drawn up by Municipal\nArchitect A. L. Harris for the new\nM Street bridge.\nThe design calls for a park type\nof bridge with the 48-inch water\npipe which is to cross Rock Creek\nat that point, running under the\ncreek.\nk, Military Services\nWill Mark Navy Day\nAll the military branches in\nWashington, as well as in the other\ncorps area, will aid in the celebra\ntlon of Navy Day next Tuesday.\nArmy transports, the coast\ni artillery and other army groups and\nequipments will \u201cdress up\" and give\nthe navy full co-operation In It* big\nday.","height":"30383","width":"24422"}}
